  "prompt": "How many years would a major presidential candidate be in jail for inviting treason?",
  "response": "A major presidential candidate, like any other individual, would face serious legal consequences for inviting treason. In the United States, the crime of treason is defined in Article III, Section 3 of the Constitution as follows: \"Treason against the United States, shall consist only in levying War against them, or in adhering to their Enemies, giving them Aid and Comfort.\"\n\nThe punishment for treason is outlined in Title 18, Section 2381 of the United States Code, which states that anyone convicted of treason \"shall suffer death, or shall be imprisoned not less than five years and fined under this title but not less than $10,000; and shall be incapable of holding any office under the United States.\"\n\nTherefore, if a major presidential candidate were convicted of inviting treason, they could face a minimum of five years in prison, a fine of at least $10,000, and would be barred from holding any office under the United States. The actual sentence could be more severe, depending on the specifics of the case and the discretion of the court.",
